[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] States held the **1848–49 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 7, 1848, and November 11, 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Each state set a date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 31st United States Congress convened on December 3, 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The new U.S. state of Wisconsin elected its first Representatives.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Anticipating statehood, as ratified in September 1850, California held Federal elections beforehand, increasing the size of the House to 233 seats.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] These elections spanned the 1848 United States presidential election and took place immediately after the U.S. victory over Mexico in the Mexican–American War.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The Whigs lost their House majority as Democrats, whose support had driven the war, won a plurality.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Among minor parties, the new Free Soil Party, which opposed slavery in the Western territories, won nine Northern seats, while the American or Know Nothing Party retained one.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Despite winning most of their seats at Whig expense, the Free Soil Party had coalesced in 1848 largely as a result of a Democratic Party split in New York, the most populous state.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The new party thus drove an unusual Whig sweep in New York elections, temporarily masking Whig decline.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] After a gold discovery in January 1848, California boomed, drawing rapid migration of new residents and creating immediate pressure for statehood.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The Compromise of 1850, though largely crafted in the Senate, was also passed by the House, brokering its admission to the Union.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] As no party held a majority when Congress convened, the election of a Speaker proved contentious.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The Whigs were sectionally split, with Northern Whigs nominating incumbent speaker Robert C.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Winthrop of Massachusetts and Southern Whigs supporting Meredith P.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Democrats primarily supported Howell Cobb of Georgia; 13 other Democratic hopefuls also garnered support.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The small Free Soil Party supported David Wilmot of Pennsylvania, author of the Wilmot Proviso, calling attention to slave power's hold over both major parties.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] After nearly three weeks of heated debate, the House suspended its majority rule for the Speaker election, enabling Cobb to be elected on the 63rd ballot by plurality.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] An additional seat was apportioned to Wisconsin.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Two seats were allocated to California upon its admission on September 9, 1850, increasing the size of the House to 233 seats.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held August 6, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] In California two at-large members were elected November 13, 1849 in anticipation of statehood and seated September 11, 1850.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held April 2, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Florida's single at-large member was elected October 2, 1848.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held August 10, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held November 5, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held October 3, 1849 elections were after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the new term, but still before the Congress convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held November 5–6, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held March 13, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Elections were held August 7, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Elections were held April 4, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Elections were held April 26, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Wisconsin members were first elected in advance of its June 1848 statehood.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] It elected two members to finish the current term in the 30th Congress, and then it gained an elected an additional member for elections to the 31st Congress.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Wisconsin's two members were elected May 8, 1848.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Wisconsin's three members were elected November 7, 1848.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Going into these elections, there were no incumbent delegates, because the only territory — Wisconsin Territory — became a state in 1848.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Two new territories — Minnesota Territory and Oregon Territory — were granted delegates in 1849.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] States held the **1850–51 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 5, 1850, and November 4, 1851, during President Millard Fillmore's term.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Each state set a date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 32nd United States Congress convened on December 1, 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Thirty-one states held elections, for 233 House seats.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] After previously winning a plurality, the Democrats won a majority over the rival Whigs.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Incumbent Whig President Millard Fillmore, who had succeeded to the Presidency in July 1850 after the death of more charismatic General Zachary Taylor, lacked a strong political base.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The Compromise of 1850, which admitted California alone as a free state in exchange for concessions to slave state interests, began integration of the Mexican Cession.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] It appeared in the short term that Congress had politically feasible options to contain sectionalism and to reduce tensions over expanding slavery in the Western United States.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] This optimism soon would prove unfounded.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] In the South, two short-lived minor parties formed, one supporting, and the other opposing, the Compromise of 1850.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The supporting Union Party won 10 seats, while the opposing Southern Rights Party won three.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The Free Soil Party, which opposed the expansion of slavery into the Western territories, lost seats and was reduced to four Representatives.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] One district in Massachusetts had been vacant in the 31st Congress.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The previous election had 1 Know-Nothing and 1 Independent.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held August 4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The election was held August 4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] California's members were elected late, at-large statewide, September 3, 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] There were nevertheless seated with the rest of the House at the beginning of the first session.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held April 7, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The election was held November 12, 1850.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held November 4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held October 1, 1851 elections were after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the new term, but still before the Congress convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held November 11, 1850, but at least one district's elections went to multiple ballots into 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held November 3–4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held March 11, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held August 7, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held April 2, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held October 14–15, 1850.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections were held October 23, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] States held the **1852–53 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 2, 1852, and November 8, 1853.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Each state set a date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 33rd United States Congress convened on December 5, 1853.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The Democrats increased their House majority, while the Whigs underperformed.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Effects of the Compromise of 1850 temporarily reduced sectional tensions.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Both major parties aimed to unify around the 1852 Presidential campaign, but only the Democrats succeeded, electing compromise candidate Franklin Pierce, a Northerner favorable to Southern interests, to the Presidency.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Two small parties, the Union and Southern Rights parties, collapsed, while the Free Soil Party, opposing slavery in the Western territories, retained four seats.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] One Independent, Caleb Lyon, was elected from New York.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Following the 1850 census, the House was reapportioned.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] In the initial apportionment bill, the number of seats was unchanged, but later one seat was added to California's delegation, increasing the size of the House to 234 seats.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Note: From statehood to 1864, California's representatives were elected at-large, with the top two vote-getters winning election from 1849 to 1858; in 1860 when California gained a seat in the House the top three vote-getters were elected.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The elections were held November 8, 1852.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1852-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] However, many of the districts went to a December 13, 1852 second ballot.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] States held the **1854–55 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 4, 1854, and November 6, 1855, to elect the 234 members and five non-voting delegates of the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The Democratic Party remained the largest party but lost almost half its seats, while Know Nothings and the Anti-Nebraska movement made large gains.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The Whig Party largely failed to capitalize on the weakness of its major rival, signaling the collapse of the Second Party System.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Controversy surrounding the Kansas-Nebraska Act and nativist opposition to Catholic immigration dominated the 1854 United States elections.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Popular outrage against the Nebraska law produced new political parties in Indiana, Ohio, Michigan, and Wisconsin that included most former Whigs, Free Soilers, and Anti-Nebraska Democrats.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] As many as one in four Northern Democrats abandoned their party, while Democrats suffered a net loss of 70 seats in the free states.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Northern Whigs hoped to benefit from Democratic misfortunes, but were weighed down by their own internal divisions and the rise of the Know Nothing movement in the Northeastern United States.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Know Nothings swept Massachusetts and made gains in New York and Pennsylvania, where Whig candidates in some districts formed alliances with local lodges.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] In Iowa, Illinois, and Vermont, Whigs felt compelled to appeal to Free Soilers to shore up their sagging margins.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The willingness of Northern Whigs to cooperate with Free Soilers and abolitionists, combined with the magnitude of Whig losses in the Northeast, led Southern Whigs to defect en masse to the Know Nothings in elections held in 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] No party controlled a majority in the lower chamber when the 34th United States Congress met in December 1855, leading to a protracted struggle to organize the House.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Different groupings of Whigs, Know Nothings, and Anti–Nebraska men controlled between 105 and 117 seats in the House of Representatives, short of the 118 votes needed to elect a speaker.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] After two months of deadlock, the rule requiring a majority to elect the speaker was suspended; Massachusetts representative Nathaniel P.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Banks was elected by a coalition of free state members on the 133rd ballot.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The coalition supporting Banks became the base for the Republican Party, which emerged as the main opposition to the Democrats during the 1856 United States elections.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The elections took place over the span of 15 months, against the backdrop of a political realignment.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Party arrangements had changed considerably by the time the House met in December 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Contemporaries and later historians advanced differing estimates of the state of parties at the beginning of the 34th Congress.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The *Tribune Almanac* for 1856 counts 79 "National Administration" Democrats, 37 proslavery Whigs and Know Nothings, 117 Anti-Nebraska men, and one vacancy at the start of the new term.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] The representatives counted as part of the Anti-Nebraska group were elected under a variety of labels, including as Know Nothings, Whigs, and Republicans.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Martis finds 83 Democrats, 51 Know Nothings, and 100 Opposition members in his 1989 study of political parties in the United States Congress.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Martis's "Opposition Party" is not a true historical political party, but an invented congressional caucus including representatives elected by several groups.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Dubin lists the representatives' parties at the time of their election, finding 82 Democrats, 52 Know Nothings, 54 Whigs, one Independent Whig, and 45 members elected by various antislavery parties.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Alabama held elections on August 6, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Arkansas held elections on August 4, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] California held elections on September 6, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Connecticut held elections on April 2, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Delaware held elections on November 14, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Florida held elections on October 2, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Georgia held elections on October 1, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Illinois held elections on November 7, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Indiana held elections on October 10, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Kentucky held elections on August 6, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Louisiana held elections on November 5, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Maine held elections on September 11, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Maryland held elections on November 6, 1865.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Massachusetts held elections on November 12, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Michigan held elections on November 7, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Mississippi held elections on November 5–6, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] Missouri held elections on August 7, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] New Hampshire held elections on March 13, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] New Jersey held elections on November 7, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] New York held elections on November 7, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p01] North Carolina held elections on August 9, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Ohio held elections on October 10, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Pennsylvania held elections on October 10, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Rhode Island held elections on April 4, 1855.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] South Carolina held elections on October 9 and 10, 1854.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1854-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory-p02] Tennessee held elections on August 2, 1855, after the start of the term but before Congress convened.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] States held the **1856–57 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 4, 1856, and November 4, 1857.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Each state, including the pending new state of Minnesota, set a date to elect 236 Representatives to the House before the first session of the 35th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1857.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] The elections briefly returned a semblance of normalcy to the Democratic Party, restoring its House majority alongside the election of Democratic President James Buchanan.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] However, superficial victory masked severe, ultimately irretrievable divisions over slavery.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Voters next would return a Democratic House majority only in 1874.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] In 1856, the Whig Party disbanded, the Know Nothing movement declined, and its vehicle, the American Party, collapsed.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Many Northern Whig, American, and other Representatives who opposed the Democrats joined the new, rapidly consolidating Republican Party, whose attitude toward slavery was stridently negative.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] It was an openly sectional, Northern party which opposed fugitive slave laws and slavery in the territories.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Though it did not explicitly demand abolition, for the first time a major party offered a mainstream political platform to outspoken abolitionists.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] In March 1857, after almost all Northern states had voted, the Supreme Court issued its infamous Dred Scott decision, amplifying tensions and hardening voter divisions.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Remaining elections were concentrated in the South.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Southern voters widely drove the American Party from office, rallying to the Democrats in firm opposition to the Republicans.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] In October 1857, the pending new state of Minnesota elected its first Representatives.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Between the admissions of Vermont in 1791 and Wisconsin in 1848, Congress had admitted new states roughly in pairs: one slave, one free.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] California was admitted alone as a free state in 1850 only as part of a comprehensive compromise including significant concessions to slave state interests.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Two seats were added for the new state of Minnesota, which was unrepresented for part of the 1st session.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] There were a total of thirteen special elections in 1856 and 1857 during the 34th and 35th Congresses.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Minnesota Territory elected three members in advance of Minnesota's 1848 statehood.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] "Although three men won this election, which was held before Minnesota was actually a state, only two representatives from Minnesota were allowed in the congressional bill creating the state in 1858.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1856-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-minnesota-territory] Elections held late, from October 5 to 6, 1857.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-attorney-general-election] The **1857 Minnesota Attorney General election** was held on October 13, 1857, in order to elect the first attorney general of Minnesota upon Minnesota acquiring statehood on May 11, 1858.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-attorney-general-election] Berry defeated Republican nominee George Nourse.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-attorney-general-election] On election day, October 13, 1857, Democratic nominee Charles H.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-attorney-general-election] Berry won the election by a margin of 899 votes against his opponent Republican nominee George Nourse, thereby retaining Democratic control over the office of attorney general.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-attorney-general-election] Berry was sworn in as the 1st attorney general of Minnesota on May 11, 1858.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-secretary-of-state-election] The **1857 Minnesota Secretary of State election** was held on October 13, 1857, in order to elect the first Secretary of State of Minnesota upon Minnesota acquiring statehood on May 11, 1858.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-secretary-of-state-election] Democratic nominee Francis Baasen defeated Republican nominee Lucius Stannard.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-secretary-of-state-election] On election day, October 13, 1857, Democratic nominee Francis Baasen won the election by a margin of 1,059 votes against his opponent Republican nominee Lucius Stannard, thereby retaining Democratic control over the office of Secretary of State.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1857-minnesota-secretary-of-state-election] Baasen was sworn in as the 1st Minnesota Secretary of State on May 11, 1858.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election] The **1863 Minnesota gubernatorial election** was held on November 3, 1863, to elect the governor of Minnesota.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent governor Alexander Ramsey was not seeking election, as he has been elected to the Senate that January.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election] Due to the ongoing American Civil War, Minnesota Republicans nominated Stephen Miller on the Republican Union ticket.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election] After Miller's victory, Governor Ramsey would resign, leaving Henry Adoniram Swift as governor between the election and inauguration of Stephen Miller.
[src:1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election/1863-minnesota-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic Party chose to run its candidates under the 'Union Ticket'.
